                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d266">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 861.77/48</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to the
                        Ambassador in Russia</hi> (<persName corresp="#p_FDR1" type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Francis</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram]</seg>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1917-04-16T17:00:00-05:00">
                            <hi rend="italic">April 16, 1917, 5 p.m.</hi>
                        </date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>1324. Your 1179. You may inform Russian Government that there was a meeting
                    to-day of the representatives of the car manufacturers and of the locomotive
                    manufacturers having orders for the Russian Government. They agreed to give
                    precedence to these offers over any orders for domestic consumption. The
                    railroads have agreed to help in seeing that the manufacturers obtain the raw
                    materials promptly and also in seeing that the orders, when completed, are
                    shipped promptly. It is believed that all possible speed will be given to these
                    orders.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_LR1">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Lansing</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
